properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham.

  • Moderate flooding is possible at Barham. Flooding is no longer expected at Torrumbarry, where river levels peaked below the minor flood level over the weekend.
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir peaked at 7.16m around midday Saturday, below the minor flood level (7.30m). The river is currently at 7.13m and falling slowly.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.67m and rising slowly, with minor flooding. The river is likely to peak near 5.70m around Wednesday, below the moderate flood level (5.80m), however further rises to the moderate flood level are possible.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • The main flood peak along the Murray River has passed Echuca and Torrumbarry and is now approaching Barham, where river levels continue to slowly rise.
  • A prolonged minor peak is forecast to arrive around Wednesday, with further rises to the moderate flood level possible.
  • River levels at Swan Hill and downstream are expected to remain below minor flood levels.
  • Several roads are closed in Gunbower State Forest and National Park due to heavy rain and high flows of the Murray River. Check for closures on the FFMVic interactive Public Access Map.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 25/10/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • This warning is for communities in Victoria. Floods have different impacts on either side of the Murray River. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, visit www.hazardwatch.gov.au. Always follow advice from your State’s emergency services.
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Apollo Bay and surrounds.

  • A magnitude 3.7 magnitude earthquake occurred at Apollo Bay at 1:17pm 23 October 2023.
For earthquake related emergency assistance from the SES phone 132 500.

Only call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency.
What you should do:
Be aware that aftershocks may occur. If an aftershock occurs you should:
  • Drop to the ground.
  • Take cover by getting under a sturdy table or other piece of furniture.
  • Hold on until the shaking stops.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Check your property and surroundings for any signs of damage. If you require SES assistance call 132 500.
Impacts in your area:
  • The earthquake has resulted in little to no damage.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 23/10/2023 08:10 pm or as the situation changes.

Earthquake information:
  • For earthquake information phone Geoscience Australia on 1800 655 739 or go to http://www.ga.gov.au/earthquakes/.
Emergency contacts:
  • For life threatening emergencies phone Triple Zero (000).
  • For earthquake related emergency assistance from the SES phone 132 500.
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicquake).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: Briagolong, Cobbannah, Culloden, Fernbank, Glenaladale, Stockdale, The Fingerboards, Lindenow South, Valencia Creek, Wuk Wuk
properties.webBody:
This Community Information message is being issued for Briagolong, Cobbannah, Culloden, Fernbank, Glenaladale, Lindenow South, Stockdale, The Fingerboards, Valencia Creek, Wuk Wuk and surrounding areas. 

  • The bushfire at Duffy Rd is not yet contained.
  • No active fire has been detected in the last five days.
  • Firefighters continue to black out in steep, challenging terrain. The reinforcement of containment lines is nearing completion.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
  • There are still road closures due to active fire and hazardous trees.
  • Fire crews will remain on site and continue to monitor any changes to the situation. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures. For road closures on public land check the FFMVic website (www.ffm.vic.gov.au/permits-and-regulations/closures-of-parks-and-forests)
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 24/10/2023 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Community Information message is being issued for Loch Sport, Paradise Beach. 

  • There has been no active fire in the area over recent days.  
  • Fire crews will remain on site and continue to monitor any changes to the situation. 
  • Please obey all traffic management signage and directions.  Remember to slow down to 40km/ph when passing stationary emergency vehicles.  This is for your own safety and for the safety of our firefighters.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 24/10/2023 10:50 am or as the situation changes.
